      <title>Tattoo needles leave behind metal particles that spread to lymph nodes, study finds</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new study published in the journal Particle and Fiber Toxicology has found that tattoo needles deposit metal particles such as nickel and chromium into the skin during the tattooing process.These particles are then transported from the tattoo site to the body's lymph nodes, where their sizes ranged from 50 nanometers to 2 micrometers, according to a news release by the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility.Researchers analyzed a tattoo needle by using a scanning electron microscopy to take a closer look at the needle before and after the tattoo process.They found that the needle showed abrasions from certain tattoo inks that contain titanium dioxide, a white pigment that is usually mixed in bright colors such as green or blue. Researchers did not find the same result with carbon black ink.The news release noted that further studies would be needed to understand the metal particles' impact on tattoo allergy formation and long-term impact on human health.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. A person getting a tattoo and metal particles entering his skin2. Cross section of the particles entering the skin and spreading to lymph nodes3. The tattoo needle being scanned4. Certain tattoo inks causes the needle to wear down.VOICEOVER (in English): "A new study published in the journal Particle and Fiber Toxicology has found that tattoo needles deposit metal particles such as nickel and chromium into the skin during the tattooing process.""According to a news release by the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility, these particles are then transported from the tattoo site to the body's lymph nodes, where their sizes ranged from 50 nanometers to 2 micrometers.""Researchers analyzed a tattoo needle by using a scanning electron microscopy to take a closer look at the needle before and after the tattoo process.""They found that the needle showed abrasions from certain tattoo inks that contain titanium dioxide, a white pigment that is usually mixed in bright colors such as green or blue.""Researchers did not find the same result with carbon black ink."SOURCES: New Atlas, Particle and Fibre Toxicology, Scientific Reports, European Synchrotron Radiation Facility, Science Alert  https://newatlas.com/medical/metal-particles-tattoo-needles-human-lymph-nodes/https://newatlas.com/tiny-tattoo-particles-lymph-nodes/51324/https://particleandfibretoxicology.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12989-019-0317-1#Abs1https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-11721-zhttps://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2019-08/esrf-mpa_1082619.phphttps://www.sciencealert.com/metal-particles-from-tattoo-needles-have-been-found-in-human-lymph-nodes***]]></description>
